'''Non constat''' approxamitely translates into "it is not certain."  Often times this phrase will be used in legal context.  However, it is used to explain scientific phenomenon, and religious advocations.  Such as in medieval history, for rulers to issue a 'Non Constat' decree, banning the worship of a holy figure.

In legal context, '''Non constat''' is occasionally a backing for nulling information that was presented by an attorney.  Without any tangible proof, '''Non constat''' information is difficult to argue for.